SIMPLE: hiss
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hiss
<hw>Hiss</hw> <pr>(h⟦icr⟧s)</pr>. <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Hissed</conjf> <pr>(h⟦icr⟧st)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Hissing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>hysian</ets>;
prob. of imitative origin; cf. LG. <ets>hissen</ets>, OD.
<ets>hisschen</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make with the mouth a
prolonged sound like that of the letter <it>s</it>, by driving the
breath between the tongue and the teeth; to make with the mouth a sound
like that made by a goose or a snake when angered; esp., to make such a
sound as an expression of hatred, passion, or disapproval.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The merchants among the people shall <qex>hiss</qex> at thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Ezek. xxvii. 36.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a similar noise by any means; to pass with a
sibilant sound; <as>as, the arrow <ex>hissed</ex> as it
flew</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shod with steel,⟦br⟧
We <qex>hissed</qex> along the polished ice.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hiss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hiss
<hw>Hiss</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To condemn or express
contempt for by hissing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the tag-rag people did not clap him and <qex>hiss</qex> him,
according as he pleased and displeased them.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><it>Malcolm</it>. What is the newest grief?⟦br⟧
<it>Ros</it>. That of an hour's age doth <qex>hiss</qex> the
speaker.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter with a hissing sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The long-necked geese of the world that are ever
<qex>hissing</qex> dispraise.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hiss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hiss
<hw>Hiss</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A prolonged sound like
that letter <it>s</it>, made by forcing out the breath between the
tongue and teeth, esp. as a token of disapprobation or
contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧<qex>Hiss</qex>⟦rdquo⟧ implies audible friction of breath
consonants.</q> <rj><qau>H. Sweet. </qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A dismal, universal <qex>hiss</qex>, the sound⟦br⟧
Of public scorn.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any sound resembling that above described</def>; as:
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>The noise made by a serpent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But <qex>hiss</qex> for <qex>hiss</qex> returned with forked
tongue.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>The note of a goose when irritated.</def>
<sd>(c)</sd> <def>The noise made by steam escaping through a narrow
orifice, or by water falling on a hot stove.</def> <-- or the
high-frequency noise from an electronic audio instrument -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hissing</ent>⟦br⟧
